  "narrative": {
    "intro": "The Department of Energy obligated $45.7B on contracts in FY2026 to date across 3,729 awards, with an average award size of $12.3M. Obligations were down 5.8% year over year. Current-year totals are partial (fiscal year to date). Historical annual obligations show variation: FY21 was $37.7B, FY22 was $41.2B, FY23 was $44.6B, FY24 was $46B, and FY25 was $48.5B. Spending in FY2026 to date is concentrated in a few large categories and prime contractors; Facilities Support Services accounts for $23.2B of obligations, and multiple national laboratory management and operations contractors comprise the largest single vendors. The mix of large facilities-support awards and significant research and remediation categories reflects continued emphasis on site operations, national laboratory missions, and cleanup activities. The FY2026 to date figures represent partial-year obligations and should be read as a snapshot of current fiscal activity rather than a full-year total.",
    "sections": [
      {
        "heading": "How has DOE contract spending trended recently?",
        "body": "Obligations rose from $37.7B in FY21 to $48.5B in FY25 and are $45.7B in FY26 to date. Obligations were down 5.8% year over year in the current reporting period. The sequence of annual totals is $37.7B (FY21), $41.2B (FY22), $44.6B (FY23), $46B (FY24), $48.5B (FY25), and $45.7B (FY26). Current-year totals are partial (fiscal year to date)."
      },
      {
        "heading": "Which categories and vendors dominate DOE contracting?",
        "body": "Facilities Support Services dominates with $23.2B in obligations in FY2026 to date, followed by Research and Development in the Physical, Engineering, and Life Sciences at $6.9B. Remediation Services, chemical manufacturing, and other professional services also appear in the top ten categories. The largest vendors are primarily national laboratory and site contractors, led by TRIAD NATIONAL SECURITY, LLC at $5.1B and NATIONAL TECHNOLOGY & ENGINEERING SOLUTIONS OF SANDIA, LLC at $4.5B."
      }
    ]
  },
  "faq": [
    {
      "q": "How much does Department of Energy spend on contracts?",
      "a": "DOE has obligated $45.7B in contracts in FY2026 to date. Those obligations come from 3,729 awards with an average award size of $12.3M, and obligations were down 5.8% year over year. Current-year totals are partial (fiscal year to date)."
    },
    {
      "q": "What does Energy buy?",
      "a": "Energy’s largest contract categories by dollar obligations are Facilities Support Services at $23.2B and Research and Development in the Physical, Engineering, and Life Sciences at $6.9B. Other top categories include Research and Development in the Physical, Engineering, and Life Sciences (except Nanotechnology and Biotechnology) at $3.4B, Remediation Services at $2.9B, and Other Basic Inorganic Chemical Manufacturing at $2.8B. Several research subcategories and hazardous waste and biotechnology activities also appear in the top ten."
    },
    {
      "q": "Who are Energy's largest contractors?",
      "a": "DOE's largest contractors by obligations in FY2026 to date are TRIAD NATIONAL SECURITY, LLC with $5.1B and NATIONAL TECHNOLOGY & ENGINEERING SOLUTIONS OF SANDIA, LLC with $4.5B. Other top vendors include SAVANNAH RIVER NUCLEAR SOLUTIONS LLC at $3.3B, LAWRENCE LIVERMORE NATIONAL SECURITY, LLC at $3.3B, and CONSOLIDATED NUCLEAR SECURITY, LLC at $2.9B, with additional major primes including UT-BATTELLE LLC ($2.4B) and HONEYWELL FEDERAL MANUFACTURING & TECHNOLOGIES, LLC ($2B)."
    }
